snippet.title: ROME - Luxury Travel Guide By Alux.com
snippet.description:
The ultimate Travel Guide To Rome, Italy (Must See Places, Best food and Luxury Experiences)
WORLD of ALUX - Season 1 Episode 3 - Short Trip to Rome, Italy
Get the wallpaper: https://www.alux.com/wp-rome

We recently went for a short trip to the amazing city of Rome, Italy. During our stay we documented a few experiences which should serve as a guideline for a premium experience in Rome.

This isn't a top 10 or best of, it's just our experience, putting in perspective what fine living could look like.

We recommend waking up as early as possible so that you have the entire city for yourself.

The go to Piazza Navona and have breakfast (we recommend getting a cappuccino and a cornetto).

Since we've already visited everything the previous times we went to Rome, we can afford the luxury to escape the touristy things and go for a more personal and premium experience.

We go to the Minardi Historic Winery, 20 minutes outside of Rome in the town of Frascati, where we spend a couple of hours walking around the vineyard, wine tasting and eating genuine Italian food cooked by a professional chef. 
Host: Alfredo Minardi
Chef: Luigi Brunamonti
Pianist: Edoardo Massaro
Location: http://minardifrascatiwinery.com/
Check them out, they also do pasta and pizza classes for those of you interested in a more culinary focused experience.

Getting from and back to Rome was a breeze thanks to the great folks at R.T. Connections who offered us a brand new Mercedes S-Class. Marco, our driver is a true professional.
They can build an entire luxury experience for you, so next time you're in Rome reach out.
Luxury travel to Rome: http://rometoursconnections.com/
Special thanks to Fabio for making that happen!

Rome has a high profile so it's filled with events, shows and concerts. We chose to get front row seats at the Beyonce & Jay Z OTR II tour.

If you love ice cream and gelato, check out Gelateria Frigidarium.

For the best pizza in Rome go to Pizzeria da Baffetto.
Both of these are on the via del Governo Veccio.

Hopefully, next time you're in Rome you will get to experience it more as a traveler than as a tourist.



In this Alux.com video we'll try to answer the following questions:
